					   <td>

			
			
			


<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">
<tr>
	<td width="1%">&nbsp;</td>
	<td width="98%">

		<table width="100%">
		<tr>
			<td>
				<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="3"><b>    Dark Elf Shadow Knight: Early Lessons</b></font>
					<br>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">
					<b><A href="mailto:">Tandavan</a> | 
		            2/4/2002 1:34:13 PM</b></font></p>
		         <a href="guides.asp">
		         <font face="verdana" size="2">Return to guide listing.</font></a>
					
					<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">This assumes that you have already created your character and are ready to play.  If you have not, I would suggest that Caster's Realm has an excellent guide for creating a Shadow Knight at http://eq.castersrealm.com/.  This guide is rather long, but I tried to include everything you might need to know to begin playing your character.  You will soon note after reading this guide that the idea is NOT to level as fast as you can, but rather as WELL as you can.  Taking the time to prepare yourself during these first crucial levels can make all the difference between enjoying your Shadow Knight and struggling later on to level him or her.<BR>
<BR>
Levels 1 through 5<BR>
Preparation<BR>
     You click play, log in and find yourself in the city of Neriak, Third Gate.  You have no armor, a simple sword for a weapon, 5 food, 5 water and a rolled up note.  Inadequate?  Not at all!   First, you must equip you weapon, make your Melee hotkey for it and your Harm Touch ability, your Bind Wound, Sense Heading,  Hide and Taunt abilities.  If you do not know how to do this, log out and go to the tutorial and learn these things now.  Also, this is an excellent time to remap your autoattack key to something other than &quot;a&quot;.  I used the letter &quot;q&quot; and have never accidently committed suicide by attacking the wrong NPC!  Having done these things, you must find Nezzka Tolax in the Lodge of the Dead.  He is your guild master and one of the Shadow Knight trainers.  Give the note you carry to him.  In return, you recieve a tunic and some experience.  Equip the tunic and right-click on Tolax again.  You will have 5 points available to you to train in a skill or skills and will recieve 5 points with every level you gain. Put 4 points in 1 hand slash and one point in Taunt..  Upstairs in the Lodge of the Dead you will find Noxhil.  Talk to him to get the container for the beetle eyes quest.  You can do this quest for experience and a little money after you get to level 2 or 3 and can use the container for storage of tiny items.  Start NOW to use Sense Heading. It comes up very slowly so keep at it! From a skill level of 30 on, it goes much faster.  You will need this skill and it will save you a lot of aggravation...as well as saving your life on occasion!   Shout to ask someone to show you the bank and the way out to Nektulos Forest. Make your way to the large log called the &quot;Newbie Log&quot;.  Again, almost anyone near will be happy to show you where it is.  This will be your hunting ground for the first 5 levels.  Do not hunt across the path yet. You will die quickly and easily if you do.  At level one, everything will /con white, yellow or red to you.  /Con EVERYTHING before you attack it!  Hunt moss snakes, decaying skeletons and black wolves at this level (add fire beetles at level 2 and spiderlings at 2 or 3).  By the way, spiderling silks can sell for as high as 20pp per stack in East Commons so bank those too.  Fire beetle eyes sell for over 2 silver each to merchants.  Keep every bone chip you loot.  They sell for 3 to 5pp per stack of 20 to other players.  You will not need them for yourself until level 9.  Also keep every ruined wolf pelt until you have a stack of 20, and bank the pelts.  Loot and keep all the chunks of meat you find on the wolves.  This is FREE FOOD that you will not have to buy!!!  It will save you quite a lot of money if you stay with this habit.  ALWAYS loot the corpse of anything valuable...you can't afford to waste anything!  A note of caution here: fire beetles, wolves, spiderlings and decaying skeletons will gang up if you attack one of them, so choose your hunting ground with this in mind.<BR>
     Storage: You will run out of inventory room very quickly.  To keep from running to sell so often, as soon as you can, go to Neriak Foreign Quarter.  In the shop Silk Underground, you will find boxes for sale for a couple of gold each.  Buy one of these for extra space until you can afford a backpack.<BR>
     Pulling is tiresome; chasing your prey to only to run into 3 more that jump into the fight, leaving you running for your life or dead.  You have archery skill...use it!  Make a bow a priority purchase...buy the cheap arrows and use it to pull everything!  Your archery skill maxes at 75, but does decent damage up front and most importantly, makes the enemy come to you!  You may well want to start fletching to make your own arrows (always cheaper and better than any you can buy).  One big problem is that Verant saw fit NOT not sell fletching kits in Neriak, so if you decide to fletch, you will have to ask for other players that might be able to help you get a kit.  A fletching skill of 68 (easy to get to) will let you make a 2 damage/150 range arrow that is perfect for pulling as well as let you make a good bow to pull with!  You don't need extra space... the bow goes in range slot and a stack of 20 arrows will go into the ammo slot.  An excellent fletching guide is at http://members.bellatlantic.net/~ewj/fletchguide/.  I highly recommend it as one of the very best to be found.<BR>
     Taunt: hit the taunt button every time you fight, all during the fight. You must max this in order to able to taunt a mob off yor casters.  They cannot melee and you can.  It's your job to take the beating. And with spells at level 9, taunting gets much easier!<BR>
     Harm Touch: one theory says use it every time it returns to do damage to an enemy.  Another says save it for emergencies.  It will recycle every 90 minutes (real time) and can save your life or that of your brother or sister.  If you do not need it, keep it handy.  It will gain as you do...10 times level +1 up to level 40.  Then 20 times level +1 from 40 on.  If you choose to use it in a fight, do so early.  Why HT an opponent for 51 points when he has only 40 or so left?  Do not waste your damage capability.  Conversely, if both you and your opponent are very low on hit points after a fight, it may well make the difference between winning and losing.<BR>
     As soon as you have a stack of ruined wolf pelts, start shouting for a tailor.  He or she can turn your pelts into patchwork armor for you (usually charging you nothing for this - so be very grateful if someone does this for you)!  Also start asking around to buy a rusty 2 hand slash sword.  (Remember..you are a Shadow Knight and we do NOT beg...for anything!  Leave begging to the lesser pale ones. You are better than that).      You must practice all your melee skills starting as soon as possible.  They are very hard to catch up if you wait too long!  Loot a rusty mace off a decaying skeleton and use that too.  When you are higher and can afford a Mace of the Shadowed Soul, you will be very happy you did!  Neat tip!  Loot a rusty longsword and take it to the forge in Neriak Commons.  Buy a couple of stones and sharpen it.  This may take a couple of attempts.  Guess what?  It has BETTER delay than your newbie sword and has better range on it too=)))  Use it and put your newbie one in the bank for insurance.  This goes for any rusty weapon you loot.  You can sharpen it to improve its stats and use it or sell it for a little more money as well as starting a skill in blacksmithing.  This is also a good time to go to Hekzin G'Zule in the Rogue Guild and start your quest for the Dark Shield of Ebon.  Just bring him 3 moss snake skins and 3 snake fangs and he will give you either rations or a shield. Keep doing the quest til you get the shield.  Good AC and at level 6 you can bash with it.<BR>
     By now you should be fighting anything that /cons blue or white to you.  Save your training points and use them when you acquire a new weapon or other skill to train in(1 hand blunt, 2 hand slash, piercing)...yes, piercing too.  Many Knights will tell you this is a useless skill and not worth training.  I say they are wrong.  Max it early and keep it maxed every level with your other skills.  There are some excellent Shadow Knight piercing weapons out now...and who knows what is to come?  And those cracked staffs players let rot on the decaying skeleton's corpses?  They are worth almost a plat each to a merchant and one of them will make a fine 1 hand blunt weapon for you!<BR>
     The free ride is over after level 4.  Now when you die, you do not get new food or drink, and must loot everything off your corpse or lose it.  You still have 15 minutes.  From level 5 on, you will lose experience when you die (not very much though).  By level 5 though, if you have been busy and frugal, you should have a shield, a full (or nearly so) set of patchwork armor, a 1 hand and 2 hand slash weapon, a 1 hand blunt and a piercer.  Not bad at all for a young Knight!  Most important of all, you will have mastered the skills necessary to use your weapons.  Maintaining those skills will be much easier now.<BR>
     Bind Wound: this is one of the most useful skills you will ever develop and is absolutely necessary to your ability to solo efficiently (yes a Shadow Knight CAN solo).  Unfortunately, at 5 to 6 silver each, bandages are too expensive for most new Shadow Knights.  But there is an alternative.  Before beginning a session, try to find a magician who can summon bandages for you.  If he or she will, then you have a stock of bandages to work with.  Donate what you can to him (he's trying to play too).  Remember that these are No Rent and will dissappear 30 minutes after you log out,so try to keep at least a few purchased ones on you for emergencies.  Bind wound is an important skill since as an SK you do not get a self-heal spell  so try to skill this up as soon as you can.<BR>
     One last note: if you choose to group with others, sooner or later someone will die.  A Shadow Knight does not run and leave his or her comrades to die alone.  Win with them, or die with them!  We are Shadow Knights and death is nothing to us.  This will serve as well to let others know that they can depend on you (a vital reputation if you intend to group regularly).<BR>
<BR>
Tandavan
